                <note rend="inline" type="source">706.6193/13: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-08-25T10:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 25, 1924—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 25—4:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>303. My 296, August 20, 4 p.m. There have been no developments of importance
                    since the foregoing was sent.</p>
                <p>Neither Japanese nor British Minister has returned Karakhan’s note of August 19
                    while Karakhan has not replied to note of August 18 offering to return Legation
                    nor has he asked for keys. It is reported that he is dissatisfied with
                    reservations in third paragraph of latter note and has telegraphed Moscow for
                    instructions.</p>
                <p>Russo-Japanese negotiations have made no advance and merely [<hi rend="italic"
                        >nearly?</hi>] broke down last week on the question of Saghalien.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
